---
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
import Nav from "../../components/Nav.astro";
import SiteLayout from "../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const title = "Docs: Dream Cycle — Harness Dreams";
const description =
  "A practical guide to the Harness Dreams overnight cycle, progress states, report review, and improvement actions.";
---

<SiteLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <Nav />
  <main id="main">
    <article class="article-page">
      <header class="article-hero">
        <div class="container section-narrow">
          <span class="eyebrow">Docs / Dream cycle</span>
          <h1>From idle sessions to a morning report.</h1>
          <p class="lead">
            The dream cycle is the core product loop. It turns agent session
            history into a small number of useful signals you can act on.
          </p>
        </div>
      </header>

      <div class="container article-grid">
        <aside class="article-aside card">
          <img
            src="/story-end-of-day.png"
            alt=""
            loading="lazy"
            decoding="async"
            class="aside-image"
          />
          <span class="mono">At a glance</span>
          <strong>5 stages</strong>
          <p>Replay, score, find patterns, draft improvements, review.</p>
        </aside>

        <div class="article-body">
          <h2>1. Replay</h2>
          <p>
            Harness Dreams starts by reading recent harness activity: prompts,
            tool calls, accepted changes, corrections, and project context. The
            goal is not surveillance; it is a practical record of what the
            agent had to learn the hard way.
          </p>

          <h2>2. Score</h2>
          <p>
            Vitals summarize whether the workflow got healthier. Tokens per
            accepted change, cost, cache hits, re-asks, tool success, and
            session volume are compared against a recent baseline.
          </p>

          <h2>3. Find patterns</h2>
          <p>
            A single failed command is noise. The same failed command across
            four sessions is a product signal. The REM phase looks for those
            repeated shapes and separates wins from risks.
          </p>

          <h2>4. Draft improvements</h2>
          <p>
            Findings are written as actions. A useful report should tell you
            what changed, who benefits, and what the next dream should keep
            measuring.
          </p>

          <h2>5. Review</h2>
          <p>
            The morning review is intentionally short. Accept the useful
            improvement, snooze what is not helpful, and let the next cycle
            validate whether the change actually made the harness healthier.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</SiteLayout>
